details: Literal translation: Sea of Qulzun. It may seem more appropriate to link this name to the Gulf of Suez, but it is translated as "Red Sea" in the English version of the original Arabic text.
Literal translation: Sea of Suis. It may seem more appropriate to link this name to the Gulf of Suez, but it is translated as "Red Sea" in the English version of the original Arabic text.
In the Tabula Rogeriana, the letter ق is actually written without the two identificative dots.
The use of the word "Rum" to designate someone or something coming from Costantinopolis, is often attested in the Muqaddimah as well

According to Wikiepdia, "Between 771 and 772, the Abbasid caliph al-Mansur built a garrison city about 200 metres to the west of al-Raqqah for a detachment of his Khorasanian Persian army. It was named al-Rāfiqah, "the companion". The strength of the Abbasid imperial military is still visible in the impressive city wall of al-Rāfiqah. Al-Raqqah and al-Rāfiqah merged into one urban complex, together larger than the former Umayyad capital Damascus." They are still recorded as separate entities in the Muqaddimah
